]]\"}}</ref>\n* Winner of the \"Most Successful Russian Entrepreneur 2015\"<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/finance/articles/2015/12/24/622530-biznesmen-goda-gutseriev \u0412\u0415\u0414\u041e\u041c\u041e\u0421\u0422\u0418 \u2014 \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u2014 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0413\u0443\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432<!-- \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c -->]</ref>\n* Winner of the \"For the Openness to the Media\" prize of the Union of Journalists of Russia<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate = 26 January 2016|title = \u041c. \u0413\u0443\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0451\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437\u0430 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432 \"\u0417\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0435\"|url = http://neftegaz.ru/news/view/145494}}</ref>\n* Was ranked second in the \"Fuel Complex\" nomination of the Kommersant Top Managers Ranking for 2010;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc.aspx?DocsID=1509107|title=\u0420\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439-2010|date=23 September 2010|publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u044a\" \u2116 176 (4476)|accessdate=23 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807224851/http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1509107|url-status=live|archivedate=7 August 2011}}</ref> starting from 2014 has repeatedly been included into the annual list of the most influential Russian businessmen \"Top 1000 Russian Managers\", prepared by the Kommersant Publishing House.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2568342 \u042a-\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0422\u041e\u041f-1000 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0434\u0436\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 (82606) \u2014 \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441-\u043b\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0440\u044b (\u0432 \u0430\u043b\u0444\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e\u043c \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043a\u0435)<!-- \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c -->]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Russian billionaires]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.russneft.ru/eng/about/president/ Official Biography]\n* [http://www.russneft.ru/eng/ NK Russneft]\n* [http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2007/07/30/130109 Article by Gutseriev explaining reasons for leaving Russneft] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutseriev, Mikhail}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople in the oil industry]]\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Russian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Members of the State Duma (Russian Federation)]]\n[[Category:People from Nur-Sultan]]\n[[Category:Ingush people]]\n[[Category:Russian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Honour (Russia)]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democratic Party of Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:Russian economists]]\n[[Category:Financial University under the Government of the Russian Federation alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Cyfal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling (Wikipedia:Typo Team)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Gutseriyev"}
{"title_page": "Ronan O'Rahilly", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish businessman}}\n[[File:Ronan O'Rahilly (1967).jpg|thumb|Ronan O'Rahilly (1967)]]\n'''Ronan O'Rahilly''' (21 May 1940 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an Irish businessman best known for the creation of the offshore radio station, [[Radio Caroline]], and as manager of [[George Lazenby]], who played [[James Bond]] in only one film. \n\n==Biography==\n===Background===\nO'Rahilly's parents owned the private port of [[Greenore]] in [[Carlingford Lough]], [[County Louth]]. His grandfather Michael O'Rahilly ([[The O'Rahilly]]) was an important figure in the quest for the independence of [[Ireland]], a leader in the [[Easter Rising]], who died in the fighting in Dublin in April 1916. \n\n===London club scene===\nPrior to his involvement with Radio Caroline, O'Rahilly ran the Scene club in London's [[Soho]] district and managed a number of pop music artists, including [[Georgie Fame]] and [[Alexis Korner]]. He recorded a Georgie Fame record on his own independent label, unheard of at the time. He took the record to the BBC to try to get it played. He discovered that the record industry was dominated by EMI and Decca. He then tried to get it played on [[Radio Luxembourg (English)|Radio Luxembourg]] and again found that the shows were 'owned' by [[major label]]s EMI, Decca, Pye and Philips. They were essentially '[[payola]]' shows, and featured only music from the paying label. He said \"I have recorded the guy, so I can't get it played, so we have to start a radio station.\"\n\n===Radio Caroline===\nHe therefore set about creating the [[pirate radio]] station [[Radio Caroline]], which broadcast from a ship, the MV ''Caroline'' anchored in [[international waters]] off the coast of [[Essex]], eastern [[England]].<ref>\"The Ship that Rocked the World\" by [[Tom Lodge]], Paperback: 164 pages, Publisher: Umi Foundation (July 1, 2003), Language: English, {{ISBN|0-9695938-5-6}}, {{ISBN|978-0-9695938-5-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A2939411 | work = BH2G2 | title = The Offshore Radio Revolution in Britain 1964 \u2013 2004| date = 2004-08-31 | accessdate = 2007-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/09/27/bvradio127.xml&page=1 | work = Daily Telegraph | title = The day we woke up to pop music on Radio 1| date = 2007-09-27 | author = Imogen Carter | accessdate = 2007-09-30}}</ref> In practice, the idea of Radio Caroline was based partly on a plan by Australian music publisher Allan Crawford (who had spent almost two years planning the launch of [[Radio Atlanta]]) and also on [[Radio Veronica]] which had been broadcasting off the Netherlands since 1960. Radio Caroline was largely funded by financier John Sheffield (great uncle of [[Samantha Cameron]]) and [[Carl Ross]] (creator of the Ross fishery frozen food business and grandfather of [[David Ross (businessman)|David Ross]], the co-founder of [[Carphone Warehouse]]) and publisher [[Jocelyn Stevens]].\n\n===Film industry===\nHe later became involved in the production of a number of films, including as executive producer on the [[Marianne Faithfull]] film, ''[[Girl on a Motorcycle]]'' and ''[[Two Virgins]]'' featuring [[John Lennon]] and [[Yoko Ono]].\n\nO'Rahilly became manager of the Australian model-turned-actor [[George Lazenby]], who played James Bond in one film. During production of the 1969 [[James Bond]] movie ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'', O'Rahilly talked Lazenby into refusing a seven-movie Bond contract on grounds that the James Bond character was out of touch with the times, and would not successfully continue into the 1970s.<ref>Masheter, Philip George Lazenby Interview ''The Making of On Her Majesty's Secret Service'' ''Movie Collector Magazine'' Vol Two Issue Two</ref> Of this advice, [[Roger Moore]] said in his autobiography, ''My Word Is My Bond'', \"George took some bad advice ... I knew George then and have met him many times since. He admits he made a mistake\". O'Rahilly also appeared in Lazenby's film ''[[Universal Soldier (1971 film)|Universal Soldier]]'' where both men were credited as executive producers. \n\nIn the 1970s O'Rahilly, noticing that people \"found it easier to talk about hate than love\", developed the [[philosophy]] of \"Loving Awareness\", which has been heavily promoted on Caroline ever since. In 1976 an album of songs based on the concept was recorded by the Loving Awareness Band, a group assembled by O'Rahilly for the purpose.\n\n===Later life===\n\nOn Monday 3 December 2007, O'Rahilly was inducted as a Fellow of the [[Radio Academy]]. O'Rahilly was inducted into the Hall Of Fame at the PPI Radio Awards, held at the Lyrath Hotel, [[Kilkenny]], Ireland, on 12 October 2012.<ref>[http://www.radiolondon.co.uk/kneesflashes/happenings/octnovdec07/octnovdec0701.html Radio Academy Honours Offshore Pioneers] Radio London \u2013 Current Happenings Q4 2007</ref><ref>The Radio Academy [http://www.radioacademy.org/about/fellows/ \"Fellows\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024171034/http://www.radioacademy.org/about/fellows/ |date=2014-10-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, O'Rahilly was reported to be suffering from [[vascular dementia]] and to have returned to live in [[County Louth]], Ireland, in sight of the port of [[Greenore]] where Radio Caroline was \"born\" 50 years ago.<ref> [http://www.offshoreechos.com/Main%20page.html  Offshore Echoes] </ref>. He had been ill for some time and suffered from vascular dementia, but in the end swallow pneumonia became fatal. He died on 20 April 2020 from vascular dementia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiocaroline.co.uk/#home.html|title=Radio Caroline|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Caroline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiotoday.ie/2020/04/radio-caroline-founder-ronan-orahilly-has-died/|title=Radio Caroline founder Ronan O\u2019Rahilly has died|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.flashesandflames.com/2014/03/how-a-radio-ship-and-7-men-shook-up-britain-50-years-ago/ How a radio ship and 7 men shook up Britain in 1964] Colin Morrison, March 2014\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orahilly, Ronan}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Irish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Irish film producers]]\n[[Category:Music promoters]]\n[[Category:Offshore radio broadcasters]]\n[[Category:People from County Louth]]\n[[Category:Pirate radio personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish businessman}}\n[[File:Ronan O'Rahilly (1967).jpg|thumb|Ronan O'Rahilly (1967)]]\n'''Ronan O'Rahilly''' (21 May 1940 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an Irish businessman best known for the creation of the offshore radio station, [[Radio Caroline]], and as manager of [[George Lazenby]], who played [[James Bond]] in only one film. \n\n==Biography==\n===Background===\nO'Rahilly's parents owned the private port of [[Greenore]] in [[Carlingford Lough]], [[County Louth]]. His grandfather Michael O'Rahilly ([[The O'Rahilly]]) was an important figure in the quest for the independence of [[Ireland]], a leader in the [[Easter Rising]], who died in the fighting in Dublin in April 1916. \n\n===London club scene===\nPrior to his involvement with Radio Caroline, O'Rahilly ran the Scene club in London's [[Soho]] district and managed a number of pop music artists, including [[Georgie Fame]] and [[Alexis Korner]]. He recorded a Georgie Fame record on his own independent label, unheard of at the time. He took the record to the BBC to try to get it played. He discovered that the record industry was dominated by EMI and Decca. He then tried to get it played on [[Radio Luxembourg (English)|Radio Luxembourg]] and again found that the shows were 'owned' by [[major label]]s EMI, Decca, Pye and Philips. They were essentially '[[payola]]' shows, and featured only music from the paying label. He said \"I have recorded the guy, so I can't get it played, so we have to start a radio station.\"\n\n===Radio Caroline===\nHe therefore set about creating the [[pirate radio]] station [[Radio Caroline]], which broadcast from a ship, the MV ''Caroline'' anchored in [[international waters]] off the coast of [[Essex]], eastern [[England]].<ref>\"The Ship that Rocked the World\" by [[Tom Lodge]], Paperback: 164 pages, Publisher: Umi Foundation (July 1, 2003), Language: English, {{ISBN|0-9695938-5-6}}, {{ISBN|978-0-9695938-5-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A2939411 | work = BH2G2 | title = The Offshore Radio Revolution in Britain 1964 \u2013 2004| date = 2004-08-31 | accessdate = 2007-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/09/27/bvradio127.xml&page=1 | work = Daily Telegraph | title = The day we woke up to pop music on Radio 1| date = 2007-09-27 | author = Imogen Carter | accessdate = 2007-09-30}}</ref> In practice, the idea of Radio Caroline was based partly on a plan by Australian music publisher Allan Crawford (who had spent almost two years planning the launch of [[Radio Atlanta]]) and also on [[Radio Veronica]] which had been broadcasting off the Netherlands since 1960. Radio Caroline was largely funded by financier John Sheffield (great uncle of [[Samantha Cameron]]) and [[Carl Ross]] (creator of the Ross fishery frozen food business and grandfather of [[David Ross (businessman)|David Ross]], the co-founder of [[Carphone Warehouse]]) and publisher [[Jocelyn Stevens]].\n\n===Film industry===\nHe later became involved in the production of a number of films, including as executive producer on the [[Marianne Faithfull]] film, ''[[Girl on a Motorcycle]]'' and ''[[Two Virgins]]'' featuring [[John Lennon]] and [[Yoko Ono]].\n\nO'Rahilly became manager of the Australian model-turned-actor [[George Lazenby]], who played James Bond in one film. During production of the 1969 [[James Bond]] movie ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'', O'Rahilly talked Lazenby into refusing a seven-movie Bond contract on grounds that the James Bond character was out of touch with the times, and would not successfully continue into the 1970s.<ref>Masheter, Philip George Lazenby Interview ''The Making of On Her Majesty's Secret Service'' ''Movie Collector Magazine'' Vol Two Issue Two</ref> Of this advice, [[Roger Moore]] said in his autobiography, ''My Word Is My Bond'', \"George took some bad advice ... I knew George then and have met him many times since. He admits he made a mistake\". O'Rahilly also appeared in Lazenby's film ''[[Universal Soldier (1971 film)|Universal Soldier]]'' where both men were credited as executive producers. \n\nIn the 1970s O'Rahilly, noticing that people \"found it easier to talk about hate than love\", developed the [[philosophy]] of \"Loving Awareness\", which has been heavily promoted on Caroline ever since. In 1976 an album of songs based on the concept was recorded by the Loving Awareness Band, a group assembled by O'Rahilly for the purpose.\n\n===Later life===\n\nOn Monday 3 December 2007, O'Rahilly was inducted as a Fellow of the [[Radio Academy]]. O'Rahilly was inducted into the Hall Of Fame at the PPI Radio Awards, held at the Lyrath Hotel, [[Kilkenny]], Ireland on 12 October 2012.<ref>[http://www.radiolondon.co.uk/kneesflashes/happenings/octnovdec07/octnovdec0701.html Radio Academy Honours Offshore Pioneers] Radio London \u2013 Current Happenings Q4 2007</ref><ref>The Radio Academy [http://www.radioacademy.org/about/fellows/ \"Fellows\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024171034/http://www.radioacademy.org/about/fellows/ |date=2014-10-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, O'Rahilly was reported to be suffering from [[vascular dementia]] and to have returned to live in [[County Louth]], Ireland, in sight of the port of [[Greenore]] where Radio Caroline was \"born\" 50 years ago.<ref> [http://www.offshoreechos.com/Main%20page.html  Offshore Echoes] </ref>. He had been ill for some time and suffered from vascular dementia, but in the end swallow pneumonia became fatal. He died on 20 April 2020 from vascular dementia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiocaroline.co.uk/#home.html|title=Radio Caroline|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Caroline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiotoday.ie/2020/04/radio-caroline-founder-ronan-orahilly-has-died/|title=Radio Caroline founder Ronan O\u2019Rahilly has died|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.flashesandflames.com/2014/03/how-a-radio-ship-and-7-men-shook-up-britain-50-years-ago/ How a radio ship and 7 men shook up Britain in 1964] Colin Morrison, March 2014\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orahilly, Ronan}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Irish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Irish film producers]]\n[[Category:Music promoters]]\n[[Category:Offshore radio broadcasters]]\n[[Category:People from County Louth]]\n[[Category:Pirate radio personalities]]\n", "name_user": "Moscow Mule", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronan_O%27Rahilly"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Margioris", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Andreas N. Margioris\n| work_institution  = [[University of Athens]], [[NIH]], [[University of Crete]]\n| religion          = \n| prizes            = \n| known_for         = \n| doctoral_students = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| alma_mater        = University of Athens\n| field             = [[Clinical medicine]], [[Endocrinology]], [[Biochemistry]], [[Internal Medicine]]\n| image             = Margioris-andreas.jpg\n| nationality       = Greek, US\n| residence         = \n| birth_place       = [[Alexandria]], Egypt\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1947|09|17}}\n| caption           = Andrew Margioris, mid 2010's\n| image_size        = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Andrew N. Margioris'''  is an [[Internal medicine|internist]] and [[Endocrinology|endocrinologist]] , Professor of [[Clinical chemistry|Clinical Chemistry]] Emeritus in the [[University of Crete]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.med.uoc.gr/?q=the-school/emeritus-professors|title=Emeritus Professors {{!}} School of Medicine UoC|website=www.english.med.uoc.gr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAndrew Margioris was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]] from [[Greeks|Greek]] parents. His father was the philosopher and [[Western esotericism|'''esoteric''']] [[Nikolaos Margioris]]. Margioris attended the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]] Medical School; and finished in 1971. He completed his doctorate thesis at the University of Athens in 1975, where he was also teaching as an assistant at the Department of [[Biochemistry]], School of Medicine. He was enrolled as intern in [[Internal medicine|Internal Medicine]] in 1976 at the [[Brooklyn Hospital Center|Brooklyn Cumberland Medical Center]] in Downtown [[Brooklyn]]. He continued his Internal Medicine training as junior, senior and chief resident at the [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center|Medical Center of the Downstate University of New York]]. He started residency in Endocrinology at the [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Medical Center, City University of New York]], from 1980 till 1984. Following that, he was promoted as an instructor in Medicine at the same medical center (1985-1988). In 1985, he was awarded a KO8, Clinical Research award (NIH).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Health (U.S.)|first=National Institutes of|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=QLhUmUYi5vAC&pg=RA6-PA8&lpg=RA6-PA8&dq=KO8+margioris&source=bl&ots=j1uYFWKc6a&sig=ACfU3U17NsJaumjj-JviIJXml78nEDtgYQ&hl=el&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-8YKfqffoAhVKNOwKHV4sAJwQ6AEwAXoECCkQNQ#v=onepage&q=KO8%20margioris&f=false|title=New Grants and Awards|publisher=Department of Health & Human Services, Public Health Service|language=en}}</ref> Following the untimely death of the Chief of the Department of Endocrinology at the Mount Sinai Medical Center, professor [[Dorothy Krieger|Dorothy T. Krieger]], Margioris moved his research base at the [[Eunice Kennedy Shriver National Institute of Child Health and Human Development|NICHD,]] [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH). He was awarded a senior research grant from the National Research Council in 1988. In 1989, he was unanimously elected as an associate professor and head of the Department of [[Clinical chemistry|Clinical Chemistry]] at the Medical School, [[University of Crete]], and few years later he was promoted as a full professor. He was elected as Chief of the Medical Service at the University Hospital of [[Heraklion]], [[Crete]] from 2010 to 2011 and interim Chairman of the Board of the same hospital in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2810.gr/index.php/kriti-heraklion-crete-irakleio/3105-?cookie_b4f259d6b441c36c49ee316ff51a8e0b=accepted&cookie_e58ddfe02054fb6038be2d552acae8fc=accepted|title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03bb\u03cd\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u0393\u039d\u0397|website=www.2810.gr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eina.gr/old/Press/2010/press110310c.htm|title=\u039f \u03ba\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03b3\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03c7\u03c1\u03ad\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u0393\u039d\u0397|last=|first=|date=|website=eina.gr|language=Greek|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He was later elected as Dean of the School of Medicine, University of Crete, from 2011 to 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isarkadias.gr/37796/news/%CE%BF-%CE%B1%CE%BD%CE%B4%CF%81%CE%AD%CE%B1%CF%82-%CE%BC%CE%B1%CF%81%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%89%CF%81%CE%AE%CF%82-%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%AE%CF%84%CE%BF%CF%81%CE%B1%CF%82-%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%82-%CE%B9%CE%B1/|title=\u039f \u0391\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c3\u03bc\u03ae\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u039a\u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u2013 \u0399\u0391\u03a4\u03a1\u0399\u039a\u039f\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039b\u039b\u039f\u0393\u039f\u03a3 \u0391\u03a1\u039a\u0391\u0394\u0399\u0391\u03a3|language=el|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He retired in 2014 and he has since be elected as a [[Emeritus|professor Emeritus]]. He was also member of the Standing Committee of the European Medical Research Council (2009-2014) and member of the Greek Health Task Force of the [[Ministry of Health (Greece)|Ministry of Health of Greece]] from 2011 to 2012. He is Editor in Chief of the scientific journal ''HORMONES, (International Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism)'' now published by [[Springer Nature|Springer-Nature]], which is in [[PubMed]] since 2001. Hormones is the official journal of the [[Greek Endocrine Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/journal/42000/editors|title=Hormones|website=Springer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nMargioris has 170 publication sited in PubMed, and 65 publications in textbooks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=margioris|title=margioris - PubMed - NCBI|last=pubmeddev|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Andreas N. Margioris\n| work_institution  = [[University of Athens]], [[NIH]], [[University of Crete]]\n| religion          = \n| prizes            = \n| known_for         = \n| doctoral_students = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| alma_mater        = University of Athens\n| field             = [[Clinical medicine]], [[Endocrinology]], [[Biochemistry]], [[Internal Medicine]]\n| image             = Margioris-andreas.jpg\n| nationality       = Greek, US\n| residence         = \n| birth_place       = [[Alexandria]], Egypt\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1947|09|17}}\n| caption           = Andrew Margioris, mid 2010's\n| image_size        = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Andrew N. Margioris'''  is an [[Internal medicine|internist]] and [[Endocrinology|endocrinologist]] , Professor of [[Clinical chemistry|Clinical Chemistry]] Emeritus in the [[University of Crete]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.med.uoc.gr/?q=the-school/emeritus-professors|title=Emeritus Professors {{!}} School of Medicine UoC|website=www.english.med.uoc.gr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAndrew Margioris was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]] from [[Greeks|Greek]] parents. His father was the philosopher and [[Western esotericism|esoterist]] [[Nikolaos Margioris]]. Margioris attended the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]] Medical School; and finished in 1971. He completed his doctorate thesis at the University of Athens in 1975, where he was also teaching as an assistant at the Department of [[Biochemistry]], School of Medicine. He was enrolled as intern in [[Internal medicine|Internal Medicine]] in 1976 at the [[Brooklyn Hospital Center|Brooklyn Cumberland Medical Center]] in Downtown [[Brooklyn]]. He continued his Internal Medicine training as junior, senior and chief resident at the [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center|Medical Center of the Downstate University of New York]]. He started residency in Endocrinology at the [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Medical Center, City University of New York]], from 1980 till 1984. Following that, he was promoted as an instructor in Medicine at the same medical center (1985-1988). In 1985, he was awarded a KO8, Clinical Research award (NIH).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Health (U.S.)|first=National Institutes of|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=QLhUmUYi5vAC&pg=RA6-PA8&lpg=RA6-PA8&dq=KO8+margioris&source=bl&ots=j1uYFWKc6a&sig=ACfU3U17NsJaumjj-JviIJXml78nEDtgYQ&hl=el&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-8YKfqffoAhVKNOwKHV4sAJwQ6AEwAXoECCkQNQ#v=onepage&q=KO8%20margioris&f=false|title=New Grants and Awards|publisher=Department of Health & Human Services, Public Health Service|language=en}}</ref> Following the untimely death of the Chief of the Department of Endocrinology at the Mount Sinai Medical Center, professor [[Dorothy Krieger|Dorothy T. Krieger]], Margioris moved his research base at the [[Eunice Kennedy Shriver National Institute of Child Health and Human Development|NICHD,]] [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH). He was awarded a senior research grant from the National Research Council in 1988. In 1989, he was unanimously elected as an associate professor and head of the Department of [[Clinical chemistry|Clinical Chemistry]] at the Medical School, [[University of Crete]], and few years later he was promoted as a full professor. He was elected as Chief of the Medical Service at the University Hospital of [[Heraklion]], [[Crete]] from 2010 to 2011 and interim Chairman of the Board of the same hospital in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2810.gr/index.php/kriti-heraklion-crete-irakleio/3105-?cookie_b4f259d6b441c36c49ee316ff51a8e0b=accepted&cookie_e58ddfe02054fb6038be2d552acae8fc=accepted|title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03bb\u03cd\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u0393\u039d\u0397|website=www.2810.gr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eina.gr/old/Press/2010/press110310c.htm|title=\u039f \u03ba\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03b3\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03c7\u03c1\u03ad\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u0393\u039d\u0397|last=|first=|date=|website=eina.gr|language=Greek|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He was later elected as Dean of the School of Medicine, University of Crete, from 2011 to 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isarkadias.gr/37796/news/%CE%BF-%CE%B1%CE%BD%CE%B4%CF%81%CE%AD%CE%B1%CF%82-%CE%BC%CE%B1%CF%81%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%89%CF%81%CE%AE%CF%82-%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%AE%CF%84%CE%BF%CF%81%CE%B1%CF%82-%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%82-%CE%B9%CE%B1/|title=\u039f \u0391\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c3\u03bc\u03ae\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u039a\u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u2013 \u0399\u0391\u03a4\u03a1\u0399\u039a\u039f\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039b\u039b\u039f\u0393\u039f\u03a3 \u0391\u03a1\u039a\u0391\u0394\u0399\u0391\u03a3|language=el|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He retired in 2014 and he has since be elected as a [[Emeritus|professor Emeritus]]. He was also member of the Standing Committee of the European Medical Research Council (2009-2014) and member of the Greek Health Task Force of the [[Ministry of Health (Greece)|Ministry of Health of Greece]] from 2011 to 2012. He is Editor in Chief of the scientific journal ''HORMONES, (International Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism)'' now published by [[Springer Nature|Springer-Nature]], which is in [[PubMed]] since 2001. Hormones is the official journal of the [[Greek Endocrine Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/journal/42000/editors|title=Hormones|website=Springer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nMargioris has 170 publication sited in PubMed, and 65 publications in textbooks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=margioris|title=margioris - PubMed - NCBI|last=pubmeddev|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Nickmariostories", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Margioris"}
{"title_page": "1993\u201394 Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n |mode=Basketball\n |year=1993-94\n |prev_year=1992\u201393\n |next_year=1994\u201395\n |team=Alabama Crimson Tide \n |image=\n |image_size=125\n |conference=Southeastern Conference\n |short_conf=SEC\n |CoachRank= \n |record=20\u201310\n |conf_record=12\u20134\n |head_coach=[[David Hobbs (basketball)|David Hobbs]]\n |hc_year=1st|\n |stadium=[[Coleman Coliseum]]\n |champion= \n |bowl= [[1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n |bowl_result= Second round\n}}\n{{1993-94 Southeastern Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''1993\u201394 Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] in the [[1992-93 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The team's head coach was [[David Hobbs (basketball)|David Hobbs]], who was in his second season at Alabama.  The team played their home games at [[Coleman Coliseum]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]. They finished the season with a record of 20\u201310, with a conference record of 12\u20134, good enough for second place in the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] Western Division.\n\nSenior guard [[James Robinson (basketball)|James \"Hollywood\" Robinson]] and junior forward [[Jason Caffey]] were joined by [[Jamal Faulkner]], a junior transfer from [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]].  Key freshman signees were forward-center [[Antonio McDyess]] and guard [[Eric Washington (basketball)|Eric Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/alabama/1994.html|title=1993-94 Alabama Crimson Tide Roster and Stats|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Tide reached the semifinal of the [[1994 SEC Men's Basketball Tournament]] final, but lost to [[University of Florida|Florida]].  The Tide earned an at-large bid to the [[1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1994 NCAA Tournament]], defeating [[Providence College|Providence]] in the first round and losing to [[Purdue University|Purdue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/conferences/sec/1994.html|title=1993-94 Southeastern Conference Season Summary|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n{{CBB roster/Header|year=1993|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|teamcolors=y|high_school=yes}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=James|last=Robinson|dab=basketball|num=20|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=|class=Sr|rs=|link=y|home=Jackson, Mississippi|high_school=Murrah High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jason|last=Caffey|num=35|pos=F|ft=6|in=8|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Mobile, Alabama|high_school=Davidson High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Cedric|last=Moore|num=51|pos=C|ft=6|in=9|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Birmingham, Alabama|high_school=Woodlawn High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jamal|last=Faulkner|num=30|pos=F|ft=6|in=7|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Brooklyn, New York|high_school=Christ the King HS/Arizona St.}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Antonio|last=McDyess|num=24|pos=C|ft=6|in=9|lbs=|class=Fr|rs=|link=y|home=Quitman, Mississippi|high_school=Quitman High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Roy|last=Rogers|num=50|pos=C|ft=6|in=10|lbs=|class=So|rs=|link=y|home=Linden, Alabama|high_school=Linden High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Marvin|last=Orange|num=15|pos=G|ft=6|in=0|lbs=|class=So|rs=|link=y|home=Irmo, South Carolina|high_school=Irmo High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Shon|last=Peck-Love|num=|pos=F|ft=6|in=5|lbs=|class=Sr|rs=|link=y|home=Tuscaloosa, Alabama|high_school=Three Rivers CC, Missouri}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Bryan|last=Passink|num=22|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=|class=Fr|rs=|link=y|home=Savannah, Georgia|high_school=Benedictine Military School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Eric|last=Washington|num=14|pos=G|ft=6|in=4|lbs=|class=Fr|rs=|link=y|home=Pearl, Mississippi|high_school=Pearl High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Artie|last=Griffin|num=25|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=San Antonio, Texas|high_school=South Plains JC, Texas}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Walter|last=Pitts|num=|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=|class=Fr|rs=|link=y|home=Loachapoka, Alabama|high_school=Loachapoka High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Anthony|last=Brown|num=|pos=G|ft=6|in=5|lbs=|class=Fr|rs=|link=|home=|high_school=}}\n{{CBB roster/Footer\n|head_coach=\n* [[David Hobbs (basketball)|David Hobbs]] \n|asst_coach=\n|roster_url=\n|accessdate=\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1993-94 Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball team}}\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Alabama]]\n[[Category:1993\u201394 Southeastern Conference men's basketball season|Alabama]]\n[[Category:1993 in sports in Alabama]]\n[[Category:1994 in sports in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n |mode=Basketball\n |year=1993-94\n |prev_year=1992\u201393\n |next_year=1994\u201395\n |team=Alabama Crimson Tide \n |image=\n |image_size=125\n |conference=Southeastern Conference\n |short_conf=SEC\n |CoachRank= \n |record=20\u201310\n |conf_record=12\u20134\n |head_coach=[[David Hobbs (basketball)|David Hobbs]]\n |hc_year=1st|\n |stadium=[[Coleman Coliseum]]\n |champion= \n |bowl= [[1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n |bowl_result= Second round\n}}\n{{1993-94 Southeastern Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''1993\u201394 Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] in the [[1992-93 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The team's head coach was [[David Hobbs (basketball)|David Hobbs]], who was in his second season at Alabama.  The team played their home games at [[Coleman Coliseum]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]. They finished the season with a record of 20\u201310, with a conference record of 12\u20134, good enough for second place in the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] Western Division.\n\nSenior guard [[James Robinson (basketball)|James \"Hollywood\" Robinson]] and junior forward [[Jason Caffey]] were joined by [[Jamal Faulkner]], a junior transfer from [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]].  Key freshman signees were forward-center [[Antonio McDyess]] and guard [[Eric Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/alabama/1994.html|title=1993-94 Alabama Crimson Tide Roster and Stats|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Tide reached the semifinal of the [[1994 SEC Men's Basketball Tournament]] final, but lost to [[University of Florida|Florida]].  The Tide earned an at-large bid to the [[1994 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1994 NCAA Tournament]], defeating [[Providence College|Providence]] in the first round and losing to [[Purdue University|Purdue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/conferences/sec/1994.html|title=1993-94 Southeastern Conference Season Summary|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n{{CBB roster/Header|year=1993|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|teamcolors=y|high_school=yes}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=James|last=Robinson|dab=basketball|num=20|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=|class=Sr|rs=|link=y|home=Jackson, Mississippi|high_school=Murrah High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jason|last=Caffey|num=35|pos=F|ft=6|in=8|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Mobile, Alabama|high_school=Davidson High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Cedric|last=Moore|num=51|pos=C|ft=6|in=9|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Birmingham, Alabama|high_school=Woodlawn High School}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jamal|last=Faulkner|num=30|pos=F|ft=6|in=7|lbs=|class=Jr|rs=|link=y|home=Brooklyn, New York|high_school=Christ the King HS/Arizona